The expression $\sqrt[3]{x\sqrt{x}}$ can be rewritten as $\sqrt[3]{x\sqrt{x}}=\sqrt[3]{x\cdot \sqrt{x}}=\sqrt[3]{\sqrt{x^3}}=x^{\frac{1}{3}}$, since whatever we raise to the $\frac{1}{3}$ power will be cubed.
Now we have $x^{\frac{1}{3}}=7$, which is quite a normal equation. We know that when we raise $x$ to the $\frac{1}{3}$, it will be repeated 3 times in the denominator. So in order to counter the 3 in the denominator, we multiply $x$ by itself three times.
Thus $x^{\frac{1}{3}}=7\implies x=(7)^3=\boxed{343}$
